"""
alpha_wave_suppression.py
--------------------------
Alpha waves (8-12 Hz) are the brain's default idle rhythm —
they dominate when your eyes are closed and visual cortex is
not processing anything. The moment a visual stimulus appears,
alpha power drops sharply. This suppression is not a passive
absence of signal. It is an active gate: the visual cortex
releases inhibition to allow incoming information through.
 
This is one of the most robust findings in EEG research.
Every human shows it. Every time.
 
What makes it interesting:
- The suppression is spatially specific: occipital alpha drops,
  but frontal alpha can actually increase (active inhibition
  of distractor processing)
- The depth of suppression predicts whether you will consciously
  see a near-threshold stimulus (Ergenoglu et al. 2004)
- Alpha is not noise — it is a functional rhythm that gates
  information flow across the cortex
 
References:
  - Berger (1929) Arch Psychiatr Nervenkr 87:527  — original discovery
  - Pfurtscheller & Lopes da Silva (1999) Clin Neurophysiol 110:1842
  - Ergenoglu et al. (2004) Exp Brain Res 158:177
  - Jensen & Mazaheri (2010) Front Hum Neurosci 4:190
  - Worden et al. (2000) J Neurosci 20:RC63
 
pip install matplotlib numpy scipy
"""
 
